BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:17960
DTSTAMP:20260311T170241Z
SUMMARY:We The Native People
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.skokielibrary.info/event/we-native-people-17960
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20251216T194307Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260126T220440Z
DESCRIPTION:How did the signing of the Declaration of Independence affect t
 he Native American people? How did the government and its people view Nati
 ve Americans\, and what were the consequences of those views? Kim Sigafus 
 will discuss the impact the Declaration of Independence had on the lives o
 f the Native people and what ultimately was lost. She will cover how the N
 ative people once lived\, worked the land\, and raised their children\, an
 d explain what was lost of their culture as western expansion took place. 
 You will have the chance to learn music\, drum\, sing\, and play Native Am
 erican instruments. Traditional foods will also be discussed\, and a recip
 e will be handed out. Kim Sigafus is an award-winning Ojibwa author who w
 rites Native American fiction\, nonfiction\, children’s\, and young adul
 t books. She has presented on Native history\, food\, and music\, and has 
 traveled all over the Midwest in her native regalia\, bringing Native cult
 ure to life. Kim’s family is from White Earth Reservation\, located in t
 he northwest corner of Minnesota.Keyword: USA 250
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture,Books and Authors
DTSTART:20260323T230000Z
DTEND:20260324T000000Z
LOCATION:5215 Oakton Street\, Skokie\, IL\, 60077\, US
ROOM:Radmacher Room
GEO:42.0258969;-87.7580355
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:15848
DTSTAMP:20260311T170241Z
SUMMARY:ELL Literacy Circle
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.skokielibrary.info/event/ell-literacy-circle-1584
 8
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20251202T222648Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260202T204938Z
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever wanted to be part of a library book discussion gr
 oup\, but you worried that your English language skills were not strong en
 ough?In this class for advanced-level English learners\, we will read and 
 discuss an American novel together\, with the support of Margaret Feit Cla
 rke\, an experienced ESL teacher from the ELL Parent Center. You will st
 rengthen your English skills while learning more about great literature\, 
 American culture\, and the Skokie community. Limited to 16 participants. F
 ree tickets will be given to those who attend.The class will meet on Tuesd
 ays for 12 weeks: March 3-May 12\, 9:30-11:30 am. No class March 31.We’l
 l read and talk about Olive\, Again by Elizabeth Strout. The book offers 
 a series of interconnected stories that provide a portrait of a complicate
 d woman confronting her own mortality.Find Olive\, Again in the library ca
 talog.Find additional titles by Elizabeth Strout in the library catalog.
CATEGORIES:Discussion,Lifestyle and Leisure,Self-Improvement
DTSTART:20260324T143000Z
DTEND:20260324T163000Z
LOCATION:5215 Oakton Street\, Skokie\, IL\, 60077\, US
ROOM:Business & Community Center
GEO:42.0258969;-87.7580355
END:VEVENT
